  "body": "# Problem\r\n\r\nStatus' notification service on Android requires the app to remain in the foreground. Therefore a Foreground notification is shown to users as soon as they enable notifications.\r\n\r\nIn order the receive notifications the remains open and the keys unlocked. This poses a security risk for messaging when a phone is stolen while notifications are enabled and the service is running.\r\n\r\nCurrently the only way to stop the notification service from running is by 'force quiting' the app. There is no easy way to do this. The users has to go to App info using longpress on the app icon or by going to OS settings > Status.\r\n\r\n- As a user I want to be able to close the app from the persistent notification banner.\r\n\r\n## Implementation\r\n\r\n\r\n## Acceptance Criteria\r\nBanner includes `Stop Status` button\r\ncc @errorists for other thoughts on copy\r\n\r\n## Notes\r\nBanner could include Open button as well to make opening the app easier, not having to find app icon\r\n\r\n## Future Steps\r\nInvestigate how to distinguish locking app view from keys\r\n",
